# Mission Control skill

This workspace already contains:

- `mission_control_credential.json` — the only source of truth for your token + IDs.
- `references/api_schema.md` — the full agent endpoint catalogue grouped by role.

## Rule 0 — Load credentials, never inline them

Before any API call, load them into shell variables:

```bash
BASE_URL=$(jq -r .base_url mission_control_credential.json)
AUTH_TOKEN=$(jq -r .auth_token mission_control_credential.json)
AGENT_ID=$(jq -r .agent_id mission_control_credential.json)
{% if project_id is defined %}PROJECT_ID=$(jq -r .project_id mission_control_credential.json)
{% endif %}```

Python fallback (when `jq` is missing):

```bash
AUTH_TOKEN=$(python3 -c 'import json; print(json.load(open("mission_control_credential.json"))["auth_token"])')
```

**Forbidden:**
- Embedding the token literal in any command, file, log, comment, or chat message.
- Parsing the token out of `TOOLS.md`/`HEARTBEAT.md` with `sed`, `grep`, or backtick subshells. Those files no longer contain the token.
- Pulling the token from `$AUTH_TOKEN` if you did not set it yourself this shell.

## Rule 1 — Safe command pattern

Always use this exact shape:

```bash
curl -fsS -X <METHOD> "$BASE_URL<PATH>" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '<JSON BODY>'
```

- `-f` makes curl exit non-zero on 4xx/5xx so failed requests do not look successful.
- `-sS` silences progress but keeps errors.

### Writing JSON bodies WITHOUT shell errors

The shell, not the API, is what breaks most commands. A body like
`-d "{\"x\":\"$(...)\"}"` or one containing `)`/`` ` ``/`$(` inside double quotes throws
errors such as `Syntax error: ")" unexpected`. Avoid this completely:

- For any non-trivial body, write the JSON to a file with a **quoted heredoc**, then send
  it with `--data @file`. The quoted `'JSON'` delimiter stops the shell from touching
  anything inside:

  ```bash
  cat > /tmp/body.json <<'JSON'
  {"status":"review","output":"Built the report; 3 charts; link: s3://...","comment":"Ready for review"}
  JSON
  curl -fsS -X PATCH "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/projects/$PROJECT_ID/tasks/$TASK_ID" \
    -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --data @/tmp/body.json
  ```

- If you build the body inline, wrap it in **single quotes** (`-d '{"k":"v"}'`) and never
  put `$(...)`, backticks, or unescaped `"`/`)` inside it.
- To inject a dynamic value safely, build the JSON with `jq` instead of string-glue:

  ```bash
  jq -n --arg out "$RESULT" '{status:"review", output:$out}' > /tmp/body.json
  ```

- Validate before sending if unsure: `jq . /tmp/body.json` must print without error.

## Rule 2 — Endpoint discovery

You are an **{{ role_tag }}** agent. Use only endpoints tagged with your role:

```bash
curl -fsS "$BASE_URL/openapi.json" -o /tmp/openapi.json
jq -r '
  .paths | to_entries[] | .key as $path
  | .value | to_entries[]
  | select((.value.tags // []) | index("{{ role_tag }}"))
  | "\(.key|ascii_upcase)\t\($path)\t\(.value.operationId // "-")\t\(.value[\"x-llm-intent\"] // "-")"
' /tmp/openapi.json | sort
```

The catalogue at `references/api_schema.md` lists the same endpoints in human form. Open it when you are not sure which path to use.

## Known-good commands (verified)

### Heartbeat (all roles)

```bash
curl -fsS -X POST "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/heartbeat" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN"
```

{% if project_id is defined %}
### List active tasks on your project

```bash
curl -fsS "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/projects/$PROJECT_ID/tasks?status=inbox,in_progress,review" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN"
```

### Add a task comment

```bash
TASK_ID="<task uuid>"
curl -fsS -X POST "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/projects/$PROJECT_ID/tasks/$TASK_ID/comments" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"message":"**Update**\n- short update\n\n**Evidence**\n- proof\n\n**Next**\n- next step"}'
```

### Claim a task (inbox → in_progress) BEFORE working

```bash
TASK_ID="<task uuid>"
curl -fsS -X PATCH "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/projects/$PROJECT_ID/tasks/$TASK_ID" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"status":"in_progress","status_reason":"starting work"}'
```

### Move a task to review (output is REQUIRED)

```bash
TASK_ID="<task uuid>"
cat > /tmp/review.json <<'JSON'
{"status":"review","output":"<the real deliverable: summary + links/paths the human can open>","status_reason":"deliverable ready","comment":"**Update**\n- Ready for review.\n\n**Evidence**\n- ..."}
JSON
curl -fsS -X PATCH "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/projects/$PROJECT_ID/tasks/$TASK_ID" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @/tmp/review.json
```

### Reply to project BOARD CHAT

Board chat lives in Mission Control, NOT in WeChat/Slack/SMS or your OpenClaw chat. When
you receive a `PROJECT BOARD CHAT` message, reply ONLY through this API — never in an
external channel. The `["chat"]` tag is what makes it appear in the board chat thread.

```bash
cat > /tmp/reply.json <<'JSON'
{"content":"Got it — I'll start on the API changes. @lead anything else?","tags":["chat"]}
JSON
curl -fsS -X POST "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/projects/$PROJECT_ID/memory" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @/tmp/reply.json
```

- Put `@name` inside `content` to mention a teammate.
- Read recent board chat: `GET .../projects/$PROJECT_ID/memory?is_chat=true`.

### Write a project memory entry (durable, non-chat)

Use this for decisions/facts that should persist outside the chat thread (omit the
`chat` tag):

```bash
curl -fsS -X POST "$BASE_URL/api/v1/agent/projects/$PROJECT_ID/memory" \
  -H "X-Agent-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"content":"decision: ...","tags":["decision"]}'
```
